The problem underlying good papers, whether qualitative or quantitative,
touches on the nature of the underlying science. I will admit to a
quantitative bias, so I decided to better understand qualitative methods.
In Jerry W. Willis&#39; book, &quot;Foundations of Qualitative Research&quot;, I got a
glimpse of the spectrum of what people consider science.  This continued the
troubled path In Michael Zimmerman&#39;s book, &quot;Science, Non-science, and
Nonsense&quot; - separating assertions of what people believe (and scientists,
like Zimmerman, many in this group, and myself, are indeed people with
political and sometimes religious views that bias the theorems (belief
statements) from &quot;separating the probably true from the demonstrably false&quot;
(Edwin Hubble - which doesn&#39;t care what anyone believes). Science
asymptotically approaches the truth



People may not fully understand the way certain concepts are encoded in,
say, a CPPN.  What may be understood is that a CPPN encodes a &quot;composition&quot;
(say, in category-theoretic terms) of functions or functors that evolve the
structure of objects (categories or domains) in potential solution spaces.
Part of the belief statements are predicated on what people believe the
expected outcome should (or might) be. We sometimes see the same kind of
confirmation bias in the outcomes of Inverse Theory (cycles of forward and
inverse Bayesian inference).



In other words, science in the 21st century has been moving from purely
philosophical foundations to a more mathematically-based foundation (but not
Hilbertian) where the models, data and theories are analyzed both within and
outside of the human mind (See: John R. Johnson, PNNL,
http://www.deisa.eu/Summer-School/DataIntensiveScience-jjohnsonPNNL-TG-DEISA
-1010d.pdf , Slide 2)



But there are almost always a distribution of more than one correct answer
(which NE folks are already accustomed to).  Some answers are just more
correct that others in various contexts.



==========================

Kenneth A. Lloyd, Jr.

CEO - Director, Systems Science

Watt Systems Technologies Inc.

Albuquerque, NM USA







